  "description": "Growth Rates and Worm brains",
  "body_html": "<p>An update on my explorations this weekend, applying models to biological data. Here are some rough lab notes I\u2019ve made. </p><div><hr></div><p><strong>Bioreactor fermentation</strong></p><ul><li><p>Thanks to <a href=\"https://notes.livingphysics.org/\">David Jordan at Living Physics</a> for giving me some of his growth datasets from the lab\u2019s bioreactors! </p></li></ul><ul><li><p>The data consisted of 3 experiments, 4 samples each. The two variables measured were OD (cell growth) and pressure over time. </p></li><li><p>I tried to apply Hankel-DMD with 300 delays, rank 80, to model the change in these variables over time.</p></li><li><p>I struggled to get models to capture the full dynamics. But it works okay on the two regimes separately. DMD captures growth phase well. Pressure decay phase hits R\u00b2 ~0.88-0.99. Standard DMD fails on full trajectories but works on quasi-linear portions.</p></li></ul><div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2 is-viewable-img\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!0AZz!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F980074e7-0b7d-4ab3-903f-295af0dce4ac_1236x1394.png\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!0AZz!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F980074e7-0b7d-4ab3-903f-295af0dce4ac_1236x1394.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!0AZz!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F980074e7-0b7d-4ab3-903f-295af0dce4ac_1236x1394.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!0AZz!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpubli